\section{Neutron Stars}

\subsection*{Introduction}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Neutron Stars}  
\begin{itemize}
\scriptsize{
 \item Compact stellar objects with highest densities in the universe (matter $> 10$ times nuclear densities).
 \item At these densities and pressures; energetically favorable for protons and electrons to form free neutrons. 
 \item free neutrons normally $\beta$ decay in $\sim 15$ minutes, but at sufficient depths in the NS the decay reaction is suppressed as the Fermi energy becomes too high to be populated by the electrons which would be created in the decay. 
 \item Neutron stars are supported by the degeneracy pressure of those free neutrons, as is the case of white
dwarfs with electrons, but there are also nuclear interactions role in the pressure balance.
 \item matter in the conditions can only be probed through astrophysicals observationxs that measure mass and radius with sufficient precision.
 \item The determination of the equation of state of cold, ultradense matter, such as that found in the interiors of neutron stars, has been one of the key science goals of high-energy astrophysics and nuclear physics. 
 \item cores of ns: highest matter densities in nature, several times the densities in atomic nucei. magnetic field strnghs can exceed the stronges here by 10 orders.
hyperon-dominated matter, deconfined quark matter, superfluidity, superconductivy are predict in ns
