\section{X-ray bursts}


\subsection*{What are X-ray bursts}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{What are X-ray bursts}
\begin{itemize}
 \item They are bright
 \item We see the neutron star surface
 \item Spectra well fit by Planck curves
 \item Type I X-ray bursts to infer M,R
Lewin et al. (1993), figure
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\subsection*{Time Resolved X-ray Spectroscopy}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Time Resolved X-ray Spectroscopy}
\begin{itemize}
 \item Using archival RXTE observations of X-ray bursters, we identify thermonuclear X-ray
bursts.
 \item We extract spectra for 0.25, 0.5, 1 and 2 s time intervals, depending on the source count rate during the burst. 
 \item We then model each of these X-ray spectra with a blackbody function and measure two physical parameters:
 \begin{itemize}
  \item Eddington Flux: In each burst, we measure the Eddington flux at the so-called touchdown point where the photosphere
returns to the neutron star surface following an expansion event. At this point, the flux is still at the
local Eddington limit and the outermost layers are radiation pressure supported. Figure 1 shows the
spread of the touchdown fluxes measured in individual bursts around the central value determined
per source. As can be seen, for numerous sources, the variation around the mean is less than 10% of the
central value, indicating that, for each source, there is an intrinsic and reproducible limit that is reached
during the photospheric radius expansion bursts. also defomned as tje radiation flux at which the outward radiation force balances the inward gravitational force, the limiting flux emerging from thermonuclaer x-ray bursts with pre.
  \item Apparent radius: During the cooling tail of an X-ray burst the flux and temperature follow a tight,
reproducible correlation throughout the cooling with a power-law index of −4,
indicating a well-defined surface area of the neutron star. The second spectral quantity
is the normalization measurements obtained during the cooling tails of the PRE bursts.
Normalization in the XSPEC model bbodyrad, is related to the apparent blackbody
radius and the distance through A = (Rapp / D10kpc )2 , where R is the apparent radius and
D is the distance in units of 10 kpc. In order to find an average normalization
measurement for each burst, we take the measurements only for selected time
intervals after each burst started, when the apparent radius remained constant.
 \end{itemize}
\end{itemize} 
\end{frame}


