\subsection*{Distance Measurements }
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Distance Measurements}
(Güver, Ozel, Cabrera-Lavers, $\&$ Wroblewski 2008) 
We use two different techniques to measure the distances to X-ray bursters; one is based 
on the known distances to the globular clusters and the other is based on following how 
the extinction varies with distance using red clump stars as our standard candles. 

Red clump giants have long been proposed as standard candles (Paczynski $\&$ Stanek 1998).
These are core helium-burning giants with a very narrow luminosity function that
constitute a compact and well-defined clump in an Hertzsprung-Russell (HR) diagram,
particularly in the infrared. Furthermore, as they are relatively luminous, they can be
identified to large distances from the Sun.

As a result, they are excellent infrared standard candles and can be used to study galactic
distances and structure. When red clumps are identified at a range of distances, then the
reddening at each distance can be measured. By comparing the reddening of the target
source with the reddening ladder obtained by the red clump stars, the distance to the
target can be measured.
\end{frame}




\subsection*{How do XRBs constrain R and M?}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{How do XRBs constrain R and M?}


Bringing all together :
(see e.g. Ozel, Güver, $\&$ Psaltis 2009)
The observed spectroscopic quantities and the distance depend on the stellar mass and
radius according to the relations,

$$F_{TD} = \frac{GMc}{K_{es} D^2} \Big ( 1 - \frac{2GM}{Rc^2} \Big)^{1/2}$$
and
$$ A = \frac{R^2}{D^2f_c^4} \Big( 1 - \frac{2GM}{Rc^2} \Big )^{-1}$$

where $A$ is the blackbody normalization, $F_{TD}$ is the touchdown flux and $k_{es}$ is the opacity to electron scatering, $f_c$ the color correction factor.

In the absence of eerors, these two equatiosca can be solved for the mass and raidus of the neutron star.
\end{frame}




